<number box="[1177,1297,1082,1108]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="0.88" valueMax="0.93" valueMin="0.83">0.83–0.93</number>
times their length; 
<figureCitation box="[240,327,1122,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 31" captionStartId="34.[151,269,1364,1388]" captionTargetBox="[370,1190,207,1330]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[365,1222,194,1340]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 31. Antennae: 20, Philonthus testaceipennis; 21, Renda flagellicornis; 22, Agrodes conicicollis; 23, A. elegans; 24, Plochionocerus gracilis; 25, P. humeralis; 26, P. i g n e u s; 27, P. m a rq u e z i; 28, P. puncticeps; 29, P. re t i c u - laris; 30, P. s p l e n d e n s; 31, P. transversalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178415/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[294,327,1122,1148]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
); mandibles with basal, external channel; head almost as wide as pronotum (
<number box="[1228,1281,1122,1148]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="0.88">0.88</number>
–1.00 times); pronotum elongate (
<number box="[386,505,1162,1188]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="1.13" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.06">1.06–1.20</number>
times as long as wide), posterior area with two slightly visible, depressed areas, upper line of pronotal hypomeron almost completely developed in its entire length, except in anterior third where it is absent (
<figureCitation box="[371,459,1242,1268]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 66" captionStartId="39.[151,269,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[252,1330,208,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[228,1359,194,1874]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 66. Lateral view of pronotal hypomeron: 63, Plochionocerus simplicicollis; 64, Renda spp.; 65, Agrodes conicicollis; 66, A. elegans." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178420/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[426,459,1242,1268]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="65.0">65</number>
</figureCitation>
); elytra as long as pronotum (
<number box="[807,926,1242,1268]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="1.0" valueMax="1.05" valueMin="0.95">0.95–1.05</number>
times); aedeagus pear-shaped, big (4.0– 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
) and symmetrical, with parameres short (
<number box="[684,737,1282,1308]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="0.22">0.22</number>
times as long as the total length of median lobe), and internal sac with conspicuous microsculpture (
<figureCitation box="[642,730,1322,1348]" captionStart="FIGURES 69 – 78" captionStartId="41.[151,269,1936,1960]" captionTargetBox="[220,1361,186,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[214,1372,174,1912]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 69 – 78. Ventral (left) and lateral (right) view of aedeagus: 69, Philonthus testaceipennis; 70, Homalolinus flavipennis; 71, Thyreocephalus puncticeps; 72, Renda fimetaria; 73, R. flagellicornis; 74, R. leprieuri; 75, Agrodes conicicollis; 76, A. elegans; 77, Plochionocerus ashei; 78, P. discedens. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178422/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[697,730,1322,1348]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="75.0">75</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,642,1788]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,1362,1388]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Variation.</emphasis>
The species shows variation in the total body length (
<quantity box="[949,1124,1362,1388]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.97" metricValueMax="2.19" metricValueMin="1.75" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="19.7" valueMax="21.9" valueMin="17.5">17.5–21.9 mm</quantity>
), the color of the body that can be metallic violet-blue, greenish blue or green and some specimens have the head widest at the eyes level and narrows toward the neck.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,642,1788]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,442,1482,1508]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
Based on the revision of the 
<typeStatus box="[780,897,1482,1508]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">holotypes</typeStatus>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharp, 1876" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1876" box="[908,1200,1482,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Agrodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiceps">
<emphasis box="[908,1053,1483,1508]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A. longiceps</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sharp" box="[1059,1200,1482,1508]" pageId="46" pageNumber="50" refString="Sharp, D. (1876) Contribution to an insect fauna of the Amazon Valley. Coleoptera-Staphylinidae. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1876, 27 - 424." type="journal article" year="1876">
Sharp, 
<number box="[1141,1200,1482,1508]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="1876.0">1876</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharp, 1876" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1876" box="[183,506,1522,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Agrodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conicicollis">
<emphasis box="[183,352,1523,1548]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A. conicicollis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sharp" box="[360,506,1522,1548]" pageId="46" pageNumber="50" refString="Sharp, D. (1876) Contribution to an insect fauna of the Amazon Valley. Coleoptera-Staphylinidae. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1876, 27 - 424." type="journal article" year="1876">
Sharp, 
<number box="[444,506,1522,1548]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="1876.0">1876</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sharp" box="[518,672,1522,1548]" pageId="46" pageNumber="50" refString="Sharp, D. (1876) Contribution to an insect fauna of the Amazon Valley. Coleoptera-Staphylinidae. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1876, 27 - 424." type="journal article" year="1876">
Sharp (
<number box="[603,664,1522,1548]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="1876.0">1876</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
examined two specimens and assigned them to different species (
<taxonomicName box="[161,330,1563,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Agrodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conicicollis">
<emphasis box="[161,330,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A. conicicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[391,538,1563,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Agrodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiceps">
<emphasis box="[391,538,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A. longiceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), mainly because of differences in color and size; however, the analysis of larger series has shown those characters to be intraspecifically variable. This elongate species may be confused with 
<taxonomicName box="[295,423,1643,1668]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Agrodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[295,423,1643,1668]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differences in the head of males, antennomeres, upper line of the pronotal hypomeron and aedeagus allow them to be distinguished easily.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,642,1788]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,534,1722,1748]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Geographical distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[545,643,1722,1748]" name="Ecuador" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(first national record), 
<collectingCountry box="[928,1047,1722,1748]" name="Colombia" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1061,1136,1722,1748]" name="Brazil" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1151,1208,1722,1748]" name="Peru" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Peru</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1276,1362,1722,1748]" name="Bolivia" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Herman" pageId="46" pageNumber="50" refString="Herman, L. (2001) Catalog of the Staphylinidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). 1758 to the end of the second millennium. VI. Staphylinine Group (Part 3). Staphylininae: Staphylinini (Quediina, Staphylinina, Tanygnathinina, Xanthopygina), Xantholinini. Staphylinidae Incerta Sedis Fossils, Protactinae. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 265, 3021 - 3840." type="journal article" year="2001">
Herman, 
<number box="[216,279,1762,1788]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
